Rating: 4
I've made this recipe quite few times. I'm very happy with this recipe minus the caramel. There really is no need. I think it detracts from the pumpkin, which already much mellower than traditional pie. I find the key to the good crust is to used glazed pecans. Emerald bags them in a green pouch found at most supermarkets. Glazed pecans adhere much better in the crust mixture while baking. The crust will hold nicely if you don't own a spring pan. Glazed pecan are less likely to burn.

Rating: 4
Made a test run for Thanksgiving. It was great! I made a few variations and it didn't ruin it at all! First, I used half low-fat cream cheese and half real cream cheese, and the taste and texture were still great. Also the spices seem forgiving - I used 1 tsp cinnamon, 1 tsp pumpkin pie spice (as I didn't have ground allspice), a pinch of cloves, and generous splash of vanilla. When baking, I lowered the position of my oven rack to just below the half way point (my last cheesecake turned out a little too brown on top) and this cheesecake turned out perfect! Also, I wasn't sure whether or not to do a water bath, so I didn't but put put a small dish of water on the shelf underneath. Cooked full 1 hour 15 minutes. Turned out great! No cracks and just the right color on top! It tasted d-licious too!!

