Rating: 4
I've been making this for years, to great reviews. I put up with the top cracking, pressing it down and covering (hiding) it with the topping. I finally baked it in a waterbath (60 minutes at 325 in convection) and it came out perfect: no puffing and cracking, and wonderful texture/mouthfeel. I note that other reviewers have mentioned the waterbath, and it's worth the trouble. Also, increase the crust ingredients by about 1/3 to completely cover the springform pan to a workable thickness. This cheesecake rocks! Second note: don't give up on the waterbath to get a creamy, New York-style texture. For folks like Monica-San Diego who have difficulty finding gingersnaps, send me an e-mail. Bon Appetit had a great recipe in August 89 that I always use - alas, not in this database. Just don't eat all the dough!

Rating: 3
Yummy! I will make this again. I read other peoples comments and I agree on them - I reduced temp to 325 for 1 hour 15 minutes and it was perfect. I added more spices, about a half teaspoon of each - could have even gone with more. The only problem I had was with the caramel swirl. Either the cream cheese topping mixture was to thin (maybe less whipping cream?) or the caramel was too thin (I bought a jar of Richardson's). Whatever it was the caramel ran and was not so attractive. I thought if I waited until the last minute it would be better, and I kept the cake and the caramel refridgerated until I served it, but it still ran and was not pretty. If this happens to you my solution is to take a rubber spatula and swirl/mix the caramel and topping together. It then becomes less subtle that there is caramel. I didn't use the sour cream design either, I think it would have looked worse. I was hoping to make a pretty caramel design, but it still looked pretty good. It tasted amazing! Way better than pumpkin pie.

