I have made this recipe twice. The first time I used canned pumpkin (according to the label there was no sugar added). I didn't like the too-sweet, dense, dark, gooey result and wrote a 1 fork review here. I decided to try it again with fresh pumpkin and it came out great.

Rating: 4
Made this for Thanksgiving last year and upon popular request, again this year. But this year I make a few "secret" substitutions. Because I am a diabetic, I used low-fat cream cheese and instead of sugar, I used "Splenda", a sugar substitute (see Splenda.com)that will hold up under cooking/baking and virtually tastes like sugar. I also used it in the sour cream topping. NO ONE NOTICED! However, it is necessary to use the brown sugar in the crust. So everyone enjoyed it and I literally got to have my cake and eat it too. I also have some advice on baking it. Cover springform pan with aluminum foil and place in a baking pan with hot water about 1/2-way up the sides (better known as a bain marie or water bath). When cheesecake is done, remove from water bath, but place back in the oven, turn the heat off, and crack the oven door and let cheesecake cool in the oven. You will not have a problem with grease dripping, your cheesecake will not sink in the middle and will not crack, and will be creamier in texture. But be sure not to overcook.

